1. What is static in Java?
-->static is a keyword used to make a member belong to the class instead of objects.
  👉 Means: shared by all objects


2. Why do we use the static keyword in Java?
-->Memory saving (shared data)
  Access without creating object
  One-time initialization


3. Where can we use the static keyword?
-->👉 We can use it with:
  Variables
  Methods
  Blocks
  Nested classes


4. What is a static variable in Java?
-->A variable declared with static keyword.
  static int x = 10;
  👉 Only one copy exists for entire class (shared among objects)


5. What is a static method in Java?
-->A method declared using static.
  static void show() {
      System.out.println("Hello");
  }
  
  👉 Can be called without object


6. What is a static block?
-->A block used to initialize static data.
  static {
      System.out.println("Static Block");
  }
  👉 Executes when class loads


7. Can we override a static method?
-->❌ No (not real overriding)
  👉 It is method hiding, not overriding


8. Can we overload a static method?
-->✅ Yes
  static void add(int a) {}
  static void add(int a, int b) {}

9. Why is the Java main method static?
-->public static void main(String[] args)
👉 Because JVM calls it without creating object


10. Can we declare multiple static blocks in our code?
-->✅ Yes
  👉 They execute in top-to-bottom order


11. Can we call a superclass static method in a subclass?
-->✅ Yes
  class A {
      static void show() {
          System.out.println("A");
      }
  }
  
  class B extends A {
      public static void main(String[] args) {
          A.show();   // calling parent static method
      }
  }


12. Can a constructor be static in Java?
-->❌ No  👉 Constructor is for object → static is for class

13. Can we access non-static data members in a static method in Java?
-->❌ No (directly)
    👉 Because static method doesn't have object
    ✔ Solution:
    Demo obj = new Demo();
    obj.x;


14. Can we access static data members in a static method?
-->✅ Yes (directly)
  static int x = 10;
  
  static void show() {
      System.out.println(x);
  }


15. Can we use this and super in a static context?
-->❌ No 👉 Because they refer to object, and static has no object

16. Can we write static public void main(String args[])?
-->✅ Yes 👉 Order of static and public does not matter


17. Can an abstract class have a static variable in it?
-->✅ Yes
  👉 Static variables belong to class, not object—so perfectly valid in abstract class.
  abstract class Demo {
      static int x = 10;
  }


18. Can we execute a Java program without the main() method?
-->⚠️ Modern Java (Java 7+) → ❌ No
    👉 Earlier (old versions) → possible using static blocks
    👉 Now → JVM requires main() as entry point


19. Can we apply the static keyword to an outer class?
-->❌ No 👉 Only nested (inner) classes can be static


20. Can we create a static inner class?
-->✅ Yes
  class Outer {
      static class Inner {
          void show() {
              System.out.println("Static Inner Class");
          }
      }
  }


21. What is the advantage of using a static variable?
-->Memory efficient (single copy)
  Shared among all objects
  Easy global access


22. Can we declare a local variable as static?
-->❌ No 👉 Local variables belong to method stack → static is class-level


23. Why is the combination of abstract and static not allowed for methods?
-->❌ Because:
  abstract → must be overridden
  static → cannot be overridden
  👉 So both contradict each other


24. Explain Illegal forward reference error in a static block with an example.
-->👉 Happens when you use a variable before it is declared
  ❌ Example:
  class Demo {
      static {
          System.out.println(x); // error
      }
      static int x = 10;
  }
  
  👉 Compile-time error: Illegal forward reference
  
  ✅ Correct:
  class Demo {
      static int x = 10;
  
      static {
          System.out.println(x); // valid
      }
  }


25. What is the order of execution of static members in a single class?
-->👉 Order:
    1. Static variables (in order)
    2. Static blocks (in order)
    3. main()


26. What is the order of execution of static members in super and subclass?
-->👉 When subclass is loaded:
    1. Superclass static variables & blocks
    2. Subclass static variables & blocks
    3. main()


